{"title":"Bahasa Harmony: A Comprehensive Dataset for Bahasa Text-to-Speech Synthesis with Discrete Codec Modeling of EnGen-TTS.","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"Bahasa lacks a high-quality, well-curated TTS corpus with sufficient scale and linguistic diversity to train modern neural TTS systems.","method":"The authors construct the Bahasa Harmony dataset: ~55 hours and 52K recordings from two proficient native speakers (male/female), recorded in a controlled studio setup, with text sourced from Wikipedia and ChatGPT translations to increase linguistic variety. The corpus includes balanced train/validation/test splits and extensive statistics (e.g., 458K words, 23K vocabulary), providing a strong foundation for training and evaluation of Bahasa TTS models."},{"problem":"Building a TTS system that produces natural Bahasa speech while being efficient and robust across speakers using discrete neural codec modeling.","method":"They propose EnGen-TTS, which freezes a multilingual T5 (mT5) encoder for text conditioning and a pretrained EnCodec audio tokenizer; only the first RVQ code stream is used to represent phonetic/content information, reducing sequence complexity. A neural codec language model autoregressively predicts audio tokens via masked self-attention and dual cross-attention: first to text embeddings, then to speaker embeddings from a frozen speaker encoder, improving generalization versus prior concatenation approaches. Training uses a composite objective combining cross-entropy on audio tokens, mel-spectrogram loss, and an adversarial GAN loss (with tuned weights), and a HiFi-GAN vocoder for waveform synthesis; inference efficiency is improved with KV-cache. This design achieves state-of-the-art MOS on the Bahasa set (4.45 ± 0.13) with a low real-time factor (~0.016)."},{"problem":"Achieving strong multilingual TTS performance, especially for low-resource languages, with a model that transfers well across languages.","method":"The system leverages transfer learning: models are first trained on LJSpeech and VCTK to learn text–audio alignments, then fine-tuned on target language data. The mT5-based text conditioning and codec LM enable effective cross-lingual synthesis. Evaluations across seven languages (Spanish, Portuguese, German, Dutch, Hindi, Marathi, Tamil) show consistent MOS improvements over VITS and NaturalSpeech, including large gains in low-resource Indic languages, demonstrating robustness and adaptability of the approach."}]}
